    "extras": [
      "Indian travellers do not need a visa for Nepal; carry either a passport or voter ID and keep several photocopies for hotel and transport counters.",
      "Indian ₹200, ₹500 and ₹2,000 notes are generally not accepted in Nepal, so exchange into NPR or carry ₹100-and-below notes for border-town and small-shop payments.",
      "Most major heritage sites offer SAARC pricing, so always mention Indian nationality when buying tickets.",
      "The Kathmandu–Pokhara highway upgrade can slow bus journeys to 8–10 hours in peak traffic; fly if you are prone to motion sickness.",
      "Vegetarian food is easy throughout Nepal; dal bhat, Thakali thalis and Tibetan breads are the safest recurring staples across all four stops."
